product_title: yoomall 5M Antenna WIFI RP-SMA Female to Male Extensionl Cable
review_headline: Seemingly well-made and durable - longer and less expensive than competitors
review_body:
I recently bought this 5-meter-long network adapter antenna wire and it seems well-made and durable. This antenna wire is longer and less expensive ($3.52 as of 8/15) than others sold here. The wire IS thin compared to that attached to a TP-Link 9dB antenna I have but I don't know if the thinness makes much difference other than wire strength. On the other hand, the wire is not unusually thinner than antenna wires attached to other network devices I have.

--I think that RP-SMA-to-Cable TV Cable adapters exist. Perhaps an antenna wire made with TV cable and a couple of those adapters would make an even better and less-expensive antenna wire -- But then maybe this thinner wire is a more efficient conductor of captured radio signals ??

product_title: yoomall 5M Antenna WIFI RP-SMA Female to Male Extensionl Cable
review_headline: Dont Use to extend your WIFI antenna "WONT WORK PERIOD" -- Attenuation at 5M for 2.4ghz yields a NEGATIVE Gain for 15db ant...
review_body: This is a RG174 cable with 75db loss at 100ft ... this is 5Meter so 15ft.. so even attaching a Yagi with 15db gain, you will lose all of the gain the attenna was supposed to give you just in the cable losses due to the cable attenuation,  So basically 1.3db loss per foot, so 15 ft (5meters) will be 1.3 x 15 = 20db loss.  Honestly people, you should be running a 1-10 ft max to your antenna, with anything longer you are going to be losing too much signal. Search for Rg-174 attenuation... look at the 2.4ghz attenuation and it will be 75db LOSS at 100ft, thats 1.3db loss per foot. Lesson learned here. If you are looking for better reception of your wireless router, use one of the simple DIY aluminum parabolic reflectors on one of your antennas directly at your router -- thats what i did to remedy my router issue.  The one star was because this cable will do nothing for you at 2.4ghz, it is a pure waste of money, anyone saying they got better reception is full of crap. This is science, there is signal loss through this length of the cable (5meter), greater than the signal gained by the antenna you are extending.

product_title: yoomall 5M Antenna WIFI RP-SMA Female to Male Extensionl Cable
review_headline: Don't buy it, esp if you run 5Ghz network
review_body: 5m RG174 (which it is per answer) has 9.9dB loss at 2.4Ghz and 18.6 at 5.8Ghz. You won't have 18.6dB loss on 5m wireless signal unless you have 5m of concrete. Here is a cable loss calculator, if you don't believe: http://www.arrg.us/pages/Loss-Calc.htm

review_body:
I have a new router and 3 antennas. I was excited but---as things transpired the router had to be put on the floor vs up on top of an bookcase where the old one was. The old one had no antennas and looked very insignificant, and this new router was very easy to see. So putting it on the floor made the wifi reception terrible, and unacceptable. What worked before didn't now, where I had 4-5 bars of signal, I had 1-2 now.

MY OPTIONS:
1- move router to higher location---not practical
2- move router to middle of house---not practical
3- use old router--possible, but would lose 802.11ac
4- accept as is--not practical
5- try some other way to get the router up "high" ---enter these cables.

I installed the cables, very easily. They screw on where the antenna screwed on. Then I routed them up to the ceiling and checked the wifi signal strength. Now its back to 5 bars. So I am now able to use whatever router, put it wherever I want to, and move the antenna where it needs to be for best reception to/from me. Perfect.

review_body: The description is somewhat wrong. A RP-SMA Female is the one with the pin inside since the "RP" stands for Reverse polarity. Does not work with anything that i know of and i own 3 wireless routers (2 ASUS and 1 Buffalo). Look at this listing for what a RP-SMA Female should look like: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0099SHDKE/ref=ox_sc_act_title_3?ie=UTF8&psc=1&smid=A2PXC5AB6J60IH

review_body:
I ordered this cable in order to mount a Wi-Fi antenna in an elevated location for better reception. The connectors on this cable are of high quality and the length is very generous. I've been using it continually now for a couple of months and haven't had an issue.

The only thing to consider is that because the cable is so long, there is a bit of a drop in signal strength (around 5-6 percent it seems) due to the natural resistance of the cable. This is a non-issue to me due to the quality of the antenna to which it is connected but others may find that useful.

product_title: yoomall 5M Antenna WIFI RP-SMA Female to Male Extensionl Cable
review_body:
I was getting ready to move my wireless router to a more central location in the house so that every room had good wireless access, when I saw this $5 cable. What a life saver! I figured spending $5 bucks on something that might work was worth it, so it came in and I had it installed in 2 seconds. My router has 2 wireless antennae on it, so I just unscrewed one of them and put on this cable in its place. I then stretched out the cable to another room... way up high... and put the antenna back on the end of the cable. Done!
I love it.

product_title: yoomall 5M Antenna WIFI RP-SMA Female to Male Extensionl Cable
review_headline: Good Quality - Be Aware of Some Signal Loss
review_body:
I received this 5 meter antenna extension cable quickly after ordering from Amazon. It's nicely constructed and appears to use quality materials.

I know that antenna cables are subject to signal loss in correlation to their length, and some of the $25+ cables are described as \\"low loss\\" cables, and some define the amount of loss to expect. Many cables indicate a loss range of .7 or greater dB per meter of length, so you want to use the shortest cable possible.

I tested the wifi signal strength of this 5 meter extension cable (before and after installation) using inSSIDer Wifi Analyzer software on my Windows 7 desktop. The extension cable was connected to a [[ASIN:B0007XXU3E D-Link ANT24-0700 2.4 GHz Omni-Directional 7 dBi Indoor Antenna]]. The drop in signal was about 5dB using the cable, and the gain from moving the D-Link Antenna to a better location in the room using the extension cable was about 5dB. So, for me, there was not a benefit when connected to the D-Link ANT24-0700.

Then, I connected it to one of the three 'standard' 4\\" antenna that came with my wireless adapter card ([[ASIN:B000N4WRFY D-Link DWA-556 Xtreme N PCI Express Desktop Adapter]]). By moving one of the three 'standard' 4\\" connectors to a better location using this 5 meter extension cable, I was able to gain about 3 dB.

My suggestion is that you use a Wifi Analyzer on your cell phone (such as Wifi Analyzer by farproc for Android) to first test various locations that are within 5 meters of your current antenna's location. If you can pick up more than 5 dB of gain in a better location, this 5 meter extension cable may be a worthwhile option. Otherwise, I would recommend getting a better antenna, or trying out a Range Extender.
